{"type":"message","id":"a96c5822","parentId":"ad1e5c03","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:46:49.386Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_erv4xxuurz7m_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# Pulse: 2026-03-24 114615\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\n\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what concrete action to take.\r\n\r\nCurrent state:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 COMPLETE\r\n- CFI Analysis is done - found that 44.8% of invariants are noise (CFI=0), only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7)\r\n- Key pending items include:\r\n  1. CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n  2. Implement CFI filtering\r\n  3. Distinguish constant format vs research trajectory\r\n  4. Wire Breakaway to TemporalAttention backend\r\n  5. Design compression network\r\n\r\nThe most immediate next step seems to be the CFI-weighted compression experiment, as it's explicitly listed as \"Next\" in the Phase 1 Advancement section.\r\n\r\nLet me check what files exist and what the current state is. I should look at:\r\n1. `research/CFI_RESULTS.md` - to understand the CFI analysis\r\n2. Maybe look at the pulse script to understand current implementation\r\n3. Then design and implement the CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe CFI-weighted compression experiment should compare:\r\n- Current method: frequency-based compression (baseline)\r\n- New method: CFI-weighted compression (prioritize invariants with high CFI values)\r\n\r\nThis makes sense as a next concrete action. I should create an experiment design document and perhaps a script to test this.\r\n\r\nLet me first read the CFI_RESULTS.md to understand what we have.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that only 5.7% of frequency-invariants are true causal anchors (CFI≥0.7), while 44.8% are pure noise (CFI=0). This suggests that frequency-based compression loses signal rather than compressing it. The next logical step is to implement a CFI-weighted compression experiment.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md` - a concrete experimental design and initial Python script to test CFI-weighted compression against frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction quality.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-24\r\n**Status:** DESIGNED\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-based compression because:\r\n1. Frequency ignores causal strength - treats noise (CFI=0) equally with causal anchors (CFI≥0.7)\r\n2. CFI directly measures persistence across session boundaries (true causal invariance)\r\n3. Filtering CFI=0 invariants removes metaprogramming artifacts\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Baseline: Frequency-Based Compression\r\n- Weight by frequency count\r\n- Retain top-K most frequent invariants\r\n- Predict next-pulse content from this representation\r\n\r\n### Treatment: CFI-Weighted Compression\r\n- Weight by CFI value (not frequency)\r\n- Retain invariants with CFI≥0.5 (strong causal signal)\r\n- Compare prediction quality on held-out sessions\r\n\r\n### Metrics\r\n1. **Next-Pulse Prediction Accuracy** - cosine similarity of predicted vs actual invariants\r\n2. **Compression Ratio** - tokens retained / total tokens\r\n3. **Causal Signal Preservation** - % of CFI≥0.7 invariants retained\r\n\r\n## Implementation Plan\r\n[See `scripts/cfi_compression_test.py`]\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\nCFI-weighted should achieve:\r\n- Higher prediction accuracy (better signal preservation)\r\n- Comparable or better compression ratio\r\n- Stronger causal signal in retained invariants\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 11:46:38\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774367209385}}
